The paper proposes a Reinforcement Learning based approach for automated lane change maneuvers, which involves training a vehicle agent to learn an automated lane change behavior under diverse and unforeseen scenarios. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Robotics (cs.RO) sub-categories, as Reinforcement Learning is a popular technique in these fields. Additionally, the paper involves designing a Q-function approximator with a closed-form greedy policy, which suggests that it may also be relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also mentions conducting extensive simulations, which suggests that it may be relevant to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves analyzing driving policies for lane change maneuvers, which suggests that it may also be relevant to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category.
